╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  HELIX TRAINER — Exercise 10.1: Diagnostic Navigation           ║
║  Category: Unimpaired            Difficulty: ★★★ Advanced       ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

COMMANDS TO LEARN
─────────────────
  ] d     Go to next diagnostic (error/warning)
  [ d     Go to previous diagnostic
  ] D     Go to last diagnostic in document
  [ D     Go to first diagnostic in document
  ] f     Go to next function (tree-sitter)
  [ f     Go to previous function
  ] t     Go to next type/class
  [ t     Go to previous type/class
  ] a     Go to next argument/parameter
  [ a     Go to previous argument

MNEMONIC: ] = next, [ = previous. Then: d=diagnostic, f=function,
          t=type, a=argument

INSTRUCTIONS
────────────
  Match each navigation need to the correct key sequence.

  The ] and [ keys are your structured code navigation — think
  of them as "next/previous" for any code construct.

────────────────────────── PRACTICE ──────────────────────────────

CODE NAVIGATION REFERENCE
═════════════════════════

Jump to next error/warning:            ???
Jump to previous error/warning:        ???
Jump to first error in file:           ???
Jump to last error in file:            ???
Jump to next function definition:      ???
Jump to previous function definition:  ???
Jump to next class/type:               ???
Jump to previous class/type:           ???
Jump to next function argument:        ???
Jump to previous function argument:    ???

────────────────────────── EXPECTED ──────────────────────────────

CODE NAVIGATION REFERENCE
═════════════════════════

Jump to next error/warning:            ] d
Jump to previous error/warning:        [ d
Jump to first error in file:           [ D
Jump to last error in file:            ] D
Jump to next function definition:      ] f
Jump to previous function definition:  [ f
Jump to next class/type:               ] t
Jump to previous class/type:           [ t
Jump to next function argument:        ] a
Jump to previous function argument:    [ a

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
HINTS (read only if stuck):
  Hint 1: ] always means "next", [ always means "previous"
  Hint 2: Lowercase letter = next/prev. Uppercase = first/last.
  Hint 3: d=diagnostic, f=function, t=type, a=argument
  Hint 4: Try these in a real code file to see them jump!
